sea, vomiting.\n3. Raised WCC, lipase, amylase.\n4. Ranges from a mild, self-limiting condition (80–90%) to a severe condition with\nmultiorgan failure and a mortality of up to 25%.\nKey imaging\n1. Diagnosis is usually made on the basis of clinical and laboratory findings alone,\nwithout the need for imaging.\n2. However, CT is important in assessing disease severity in patients with severe\nacute pancreatitis and in identifying complications.\nAxial contrast-enhanced CT abdomen\nd emonstrates mild acute uncomplicated\npancreatitis:\n1 . An enlarged, oedematous pancreas (solid\narrow)\n2 . Surrounding inflammatory fat stranding\n(dashed arrow)\n3. Small volume upper abdominal free fluid\n(curved arrow).\n(See normal pancreas (solid arrow) for\nc omparison)\n97"}